The Deer Trail

by Justin Squires

Forest Trailhead
A cool and grey October day; perfect weather for an afternoon hunt. You exit your truck and head down the trail towards a deer blind you had set up a few weeks earlier while scouting the forest. A thick fog hangs in the air, making visibility difficult. As the leaves crunch underneath your feet, you decide that you must hurry North to the blind, as you only have a few hours until dark.

[ Type: HELP at any time to display a list of command prompts and game functions. ]

> north

> north

Deer Blind
You find your makeshift deer blind just off the trail and sit inside of it. It is a lean-to construction, crafted using fallen branches and dead leaves against a large oak tree. You have built them this way since you were a young teen, always at ground level. You sit, Bow in hand, and prepare to wait silently for your prey to enter within shooting distance. In the meantime, you had better [NOCK] your [ARROW] so that you are ready.

> nock arrow

> nock arrow
You nock the arrow onto the bowstring.

Many moments pass by as you wait. Out here in the forest, you can hear every disturbance clearly. A squirrel rustling in the leaves, pinecones falling from the canopy to the forest floor after being jarred by a breeze, the groan of tree trunks as they sway to and fro; nothing escapes you as you listen for the distinct pattern of a deer making its way through the wilderness.

The night is falling quicker than before as a waning sun competes with the overcast skies. In the twilight of dawn, the ability to clearly define your surroundings diminishes and your eyes begin to play tricks. The foliage is replaced by ominous shapes and shadows. A tree stump becomes a forest troll, off-color leaves become sets of eyes staring back at you; the imagination runs wild at this hour of fading light.  Very soon it will be too dark to hunt and you will have to return empty-handed.

Perhaps it would be best to [REST] your [EYES] for a moment and listen to the forest one last time.
> rest eyes

> rest eyes
You briefly close your eyes and listen intently to the forest.

Suddenly, you hear the sound of leaves crunching in front of you. You recognize the sound pattern and when you open your eyes, your stomach drops. Standing in the clearing ahead of you, illuminated by the last bit of remaining light, is the largest buck you have ever laid eyes on. He wears a crown of sprawling boney antlers that reach skyward. His presence is both exhilarating and foreboding, as something is off in his stature.

You hesitate for a moment, but regain your composure and slowly bring the bow up to take aim. When the moment is right, you will try to [SHOOT] the [DEER].
> shoot deer

> shoot deer
You draw back the bowstring and aim at the buck.

After a slow and steady breath in, you let your arrow fly. It strikes the deer right behind its shoulder blade and the deer staggers before quickly darting off into the thicket.

Feeling a rush of adrenaline course through your body, you sit back in the blind and take several deep breathes. It is customary to wait a few moments before you start to track the deer. During this time, a deafening silence washes over the forest and the blackness of night consumes all. You flick on your flashlight as you get ready to head Northeast towards the clearing.

The fog is thicker than before.
> northeast

> northeast

Clearing
A very small clearing inside the dense forest. This is where you struck the deer and it is surely wounded. You should probably [TRACK] the [DEER] so that you can pick up its trail.

> track deer

> track deer
There is a trail of light blood droplets leading North into what looks like a deer trail.
(You unlocked an Achievement.)
> north

> north

Deer Trail
This is a narrow trail through thick brush used by deer. The trail continues Northeast and Northwest. You will have to track the deer in order to navigate your way through here.

> Track deer

> Track deer
The trail of blood and hair continues North.
> north

> north

Deer Trail 2a
The trail is so narrow. It continues West and East.

> Track deer

> Track deer
You find more blood droplets and hair that lead Northeast.
> northeast

> northeast

Small Clearing
A small clearing nestled inside the thicket of deer trails. In the brush, you can see an old rusty car. Trails are leading Northeast, East, and South.

> Track deer

> Track deer
The trail of blood seems to go West from here. It was definitely a lung shot. There are bits of bloody membrane scattered about.
